  "description": "Gottfrid Otto Alexander Dahlström was a Swedish engineer, born on April 12th, 1895 in Umeå landsförs, to merchant Gottfrid D. and Karin Sandström. He studied thermodynamics and combustion engines at the technical university in Zurich in 1921. He received a scholarship from the Swedish National Committee for Technical Research to study manufacturing technology in Germany in 1925 and then studied and worked in America, England, Holland, Belgium, Austria, China, Japan, Poland, Czechoslovakia, Switzerland, Italy, Hungary, and other countries from 1921 to 1939. He worked in various engineering roles in different organizations from 1911 to 1945. He was a member of the Swedish invention association and several other technical societies and commissions, and was a ship inspector in 1945 and a battalion commander in the air defense from 1940 to 1942. He received about 30 Swedish and international patents for machines, motor vehicles, combustion engines, aircraft utensils, weapons, machine tools, and tools, among other things. His hobbies were sailing and sports."
